1
00:00:00,050 --> 00:00:08,149
You're listening to: Core Web Vitals for Backend Engineers: TTFB, Caching & Server-Side Wins (2026).

2
00:00:08,149 --> 00:00:15,480
Most Core Web Vitals advice targets frontend developers, but LCP and INP problems usually start at the server.

3
00:00:15,480 --> 00:00:27,295
This guide covers the backend half: TTFB budgets, connection pooling, cache strategy, streaming SSR, CDN headers, and compression — with the production numbers behind each fix.

4
00:00:27,295 --> 00:00:28,377
Let's get started.

5
00:00:28,377 --> 00:00:36,093
Core Web Vitals are usually framed as a frontend problem — optimize images, defer scripts, reserve layout space.

6
00:00:36,093 --> 00:00:49,915
But look at where the time actually goes on a slow page load and the story changes: Largest Contentful Paint (LCP) cannot be faster than your Time to First Byte (TTFB), and TTFB is pure backend.

7
00:00:49,915 --> 00:01:01,754
Google's 2026 core updates lean harder on technical performance than ever, which means the server side of Web Vitals is now an SEO ranking input, not just an infrastructure metric.

8
00:01:01,754 --> 00:01:09,074
This is the backend engineer's guide to Web Vitals — the layer below the framework, where the biggest wins usually live.

9
00:01:09,074 --> 00:01:13,112
Now, let's talk about Which Core Web Vitals does the backend control?.

10
00:01:13,112 --> 00:01:22,632
The three Core Web Vitals in 2026 are LCP (loading), INP (interactivity), and CLS (visual stability).

11
00:01:22,632 --> 00:01:24,867
The backend's fingerprints are on two of them:

12
00:01:24,867 --> 00:01:27,932
Metric, Good threshold, Backend's share.

13
00:01:27,932 --> 00:01:38,137
LCP, ≤ 2.5s, TTFB + HTML generation + asset delivery — often 60%+ of the budget.

14
00:01:38,137 --> 00:01:47,031
INP, ≤ 200ms, JS bundle size you force on the client; API latency behind interactions.

15
00:01:47,031 --> 00:01:55,444
CLS, ≤ 0.1, Mostly frontend, but late-arriving server data causes shifts too.

16
00:01:55,444 --> 00:02:05,036
The brutal math: if your TTFB is 1.8 seconds, your LCP is over 2.5 seconds before a single byte of CSS arrives.

17
00:02:05,036 --> 00:02:09,399
No amount of image optimization rescues a slow server.

18
00:02:09,399 --> 00:02:19,675
Google's own guidance puts a good TTFB at under 800ms; for server-rendered pages I budget 200–400ms at p75.

19
00:02:19,675 --> 00:02:22,656
Moving on to What actually makes TTFB slow?.

20
00:02:22,656 --> 00:02:30,048
In every production system I've profiled, TTFB problems come from the same short list, in roughly this order:

21
00:02:30,048 --> 00:02:32,968
1. Database queries on the request path.

22
00:02:32,968 --> 00:02:41,730
The classic: a page that runs 4 sequential queries at 80ms each has spent 320ms before rendering starts.

23
00:02:41,730 --> 00:02:50,132
Fixes are well known — indexes, batching, denormalized read models — but the highest-leverage one is usually connection pooling.

24
00:02:50,132 --> 00:02:58,762
A request that waits 150ms to acquire a connection has lost 150ms of LCP budget doing nothing.

25
00:02:58,762 --> 00:03:02,331
2. Cache misses, and worse, cache stampedes.

26
00:03:02,331 --> 00:03:12,932
A cached page at 20ms that occasionally takes 2s on a miss has a fine median and a terrible p75 — and Core Web Vitals are measured at p75.

27
00:03:12,932 --> 00:03:21,670
When a hot key expires and 4,000 requests hit the database at once, your "fast" site fails Web Vitals for everyone in that window.

28
00:03:21,670 --> 00:03:31,887
I wrote up exactly that failure in my Redis cache stampede war story; the fixes (lock-and-recompute, TTL jitter, stale-while-revalidate) are all server-side.

29
00:03:31,887 --> 00:03:34,771
3. Render-blocking external calls.

30
00:03:34,771 --> 00:03:40,168
CMS APIs, auth checks, feature-flag services on the critical path.

31
00:03:40,168 --> 00:03:43,629
Each one adds its own p99 to yours.

32
00:03:43,629 --> 00:03:47,475
Move them off-path, cache them, or accept stale values.

33
00:03:47,475 --> 00:03:50,829
4. Cold starts and slow runtimes.

34
00:03:50,829 --> 00:03:56,911
Serverless cold starts of 500ms–2s land directly in TTFB.

35
00:03:56,911 --> 00:04:05,324
Provisioned concurrency, edge runtimes, or just a boring always-warm container all fix it — pick by cost profile.

36
00:04:05,324 --> 00:04:09,194
Next up: How does static generation change the equation?.

37
00:04:09,194 --> 00:04:12,620
The cheapest TTFB is the one where no code runs.

38
00:04:12,620 --> 00:04:22,115
For content that's known at build time — blog posts, docs, marketing pages — static generation turns every request into a CDN file read:

39
00:04:22,115 --> 00:04:27,992
This site prerenders 190+ pages (every post plus every tag hub) at build time.

40
00:04:27,992 --> 00:04:35,084
TTFB from the CDN edge is consistently double-digit milliseconds — there is no server to be slow.

41
00:04:35,084 --> 00:04:38,353
Two backend caveats that bite people at scale:

42
00:04:38,353 --> 00:04:41,514
Tip: Memoize your data layer during builds.

43
00:04:41,514 --> 00:04:47,536
A static export that prerenders hundreds of pages will call your "get all posts" function hundreds of times.

44
00:04:47,536 --> 00:04:55,012
Mine reads and parses 80+ markdown files; without a module-level cache the tag-page export timed out.

45
00:04:55,012 --> 00:04:58,125
One memoized read per worker fixed it.

46
00:04:58,130 --> 00:05:11,529
For pages that can't be fully static, streaming SSR is the middle ground: flush the shell immediately (fast first byte, fast LCP for above-the-fold content) and stream the slow parts as they resolve.

47
00:05:11,529 --> 00:05:20,027
React Suspense boundaries in App Router give you this almost for free — the key design decision is which data is allowed to block the shell.

48
00:05:20,027 --> 00:05:22,527
The answer should be: almost none of it.

49
00:05:22,527 --> 00:05:26,914
Let's explore What HTTP caching headers should your responses send?.

50
00:05:26,914 --> 00:05:32,791
CDN-friendly cache headers are the highest ROI lines of config in web performance.

51
00:05:32,791 --> 00:05:36,878
The pattern that covers most cases is stale-while-revalidate:

52
00:05:36,878 --> 00:05:46,012
This tells the CDN: serve from cache for an hour, and for up to a day after that, serve the stale copy instantly while refreshing in the background.

53
00:05:46,012 --> 00:05:54,089
Users never wait on regeneration; your origin sees a trickle of revalidation requests instead of traffic spikes.

54
00:05:54,089 --> 00:05:58,692
I use exactly this header on my RSS feed and generated text routes.

55
00:05:58,692 --> 00:06:14,450
The companion rule: immutable assets (hashed JS/CSS/fonts) get max-age=31536000, immutable, and HTML gets short or no client caching with CDN-level caching behind it.

56
00:06:14,450 --> 00:06:21,721
Mixing those up — long-caching HTML, short-caching assets — is one of the most common Web Vitals own-goals.

57
00:06:21,721 --> 00:06:32,659
Compression is the other free win: Brotli at the CDN edge typically cuts HTML/JSON transfer 15–25% over gzip.

58
00:06:32,659 --> 00:06:35,976
You set it once and it pays on every request forever.

59
00:06:35,976 --> 00:06:39,402
Now let's look at How does backend discipline improve INP?.

60
00:06:39,402 --> 00:06:48,620
INP (Interaction to Next Paint) replaced FID in 2024 and measures all interactions, making it much harder to game.

61
00:06:48,620 --> 00:06:51,469
Two backend-adjacent decisions dominate it:

62
00:06:51,469 --> 00:06:54,378
Ship less JavaScript by doing work on the server.

63
00:06:54,378 --> 00:07:01,445
Every kilobyte of client JS is parse/compile/execute time on a mid-range phone.

64
00:07:01,445 --> 00:07:07,551
The pattern I keep returning to: move rendering work server-side and ship finished HTML.

65
00:07:07,551 --> 00:07:23,019
When I moved this blog's markdown rendering (including syntax highlighting) from a client component to the server, the client lost ~95 lines of parsing logic and an entire highlighting library it never needed — readers' devices now do zero markdown work.

66
00:07:23,019 --> 00:07:26,217
Make the APIs behind interactions fast.

67
00:07:26,217 --> 00:07:33,656
A search box that calls an endpoint with a 600ms p75 will feel broken regardless of frontend polish.

68
00:07:33,656 --> 00:07:47,394
Interaction-path endpoints deserve the same latency budgets as page loads: p75 under 200ms, p99 under 500ms, measured per endpoint, alerted like an SLO.

69
00:07:47,394 --> 00:07:55,988
The async patterns in my long-running APIs guide apply directly: anything slower than the budget becomes a job, not a blocking call.

70
00:07:55,988 --> 00:07:59,498
Now, let's talk about How do you measure Web Vitals like a backend engineer?.

71
00:07:59,498 --> 00:08:05,760
Lab tools (Lighthouse) are for debugging; field data is what Google ranks you on.

72
00:08:05,760 --> 00:08:07,382
The pipeline that works:

73
00:08:07,382 --> 00:08:16,000
CrUX / Search Console — the ground truth Google sees, at p75, per origin and per URL group.

74
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:17,010
Check it monthly..

75
00:08:17,010 --> 00:08:25,832
RUM beacons — the web-vitals JS library posts LCP/INP/CLS to a collection endpoint.

76
00:08:25,832 --> 00:08:29,991
Store them like any other metric; graph p75 by route..

77
00:08:29,991 --> 00:08:34,786
Server-side TTFB histograms — you already have these in your APM.

78
00:08:34,786 --> 00:08:40,171
Correlate spikes against deploys, cache hit rates, and DB pool saturation.

79
00:08:40,171 --> 00:08:43,356
(The instrumentation stack is in my observability guide.).

80
00:08:43,356 --> 00:08:54,702
The habit that matters: treat a Web Vitals regression like an API latency regression — bisect by layer (CDN → origin → app → DB) instead of reaching for frontend tweaks first.

81
00:08:54,702 --> 00:08:57,575
The waterfall doesn't lie about where the time went.

82
00:08:57,575 --> 00:09:00,616
Moving on to The backend Web Vitals checklist.

83
00:09:00,616 --> 00:09:08,692
TTFB p75 under 400ms for SSR routes; static-generate everything that can be.

84
00:09:08,692 --> 00:09:14,185
Connection pools sized and monitored; no pool-wait time on the request path.

85
00:09:14,185 --> 00:09:20,652
Cache stampede protection on every hot key (locks + jitter + stale-while-revalidate).

86
00:09:20,652 --> 00:09:26,866
stale-while-revalidate CDN headers on dynamic-ish content; immutable on hashed assets.

87
00:09:26,866 --> 00:09:28,849
Brotli compression at the edge.

88
00:09:28,849 --> 00:09:33,416
Streaming SSR with nothing non-essential blocking the shell.

89
00:09:33,416 --> 00:09:41,601
Server-side rendering of expensive transforms (markdown, highlighting, charts) — ship HTML, not libraries.

90
00:09:41,601 --> 00:09:47,851
Interaction-path API budgets: p75 < 200ms, alerted.

91
00:09:47,851 --> 00:09:53,765
Field data (CrUX + RUM) reviewed monthly, regressions bisected by layer.

92
00:09:53,810 --> 00:10:00,334
Core Web Vitals being "a frontend metric" is the most expensive misconception in web performance.

93
00:10:00,334 --> 00:10:05,671
The frontend spends the latency budget — but the backend decides how big the budget is.

94
00:10:05,671 --> 00:10:07,425
And that's the end of this article.

95
00:10:07,425 --> 00:10:08,531
Thanks for listening.

